args: You really are an unpleasant person,\nNevin.
What a thing to say! I'll have you know\neveryone always says what a fine piece\nof work I am.
That's not the compliment you think it is...\nBut never mind you for now.
Ryszarda was telling me how much fun\nyou seemed to be having cornering her\nduring your mission.
I didn't have a choice! I couldn't act like\nI was on her sideâ€”and it gave me no\njoy to be fighting her, I assure you.
Although he has been known to\nenjoy venting his work frustrations\nlike that in the past.
If there's something you wanna say,\ngo ahead and say it, Pinon.
I'm just thinking it's no wonder why\neveryone connected to the Church\nhates you.
Ouch. Tell Papa Bear how you REALLY feel.\nAnyway, where'd you get the idea people\nhate me? That hurts if it's true!
I... I'm so sorry I'm late!
I was attacked by bandits four times on\nthe way hereâ€”I'm sorry! I don't want to\nsound like I'm making excuses!
That doesn't sound very enjoyable.\nIncidentally, have you spoken to\nRaphael since, well...the incident?
I can't say I have.\nDid she need something from me?

Oh, not especially. But after reporting
the events that transpired, Sandalphon
relayed her response, and she had some...
choice words for me.
I'm so sorry.\nUm... What did she say?
She said something along the lines of,\nï¼‚I'M the only one allowed to chuck my\nli'l one off a cliff!ï¼‚
That's...not quite the complaint I was\nexpecting.
Still your tongues and pay heed.
I have come to inform you of your next\nmission.
But first, I have further information\nconcerning the mission with which\nthree of you were recently involved.
Correct. He took his own life.
What?! Then we didn't get anything out\nof him?!
Indeed. No testimony regarding the\nanti-apostle camp in the Church could\nbe obtained before his untimely demise.
I must be missing part of the story here.
This is about the mission we were\ndiscussing earlier.
The bishop responsible for the case\nwas a sympathizer of those who\ndespise apostles.
But we're all followers of the same\nGoddess...
I'd long known there were those in the\nChurch who didn't like us...but until now,\nthey rarely visibly acted on that hate.

I investigated the bishop in this
case, and learned that his dislike of
angels and apostles began suddenly
a few months ago.
Normally, one would assume there was\nan inciting incident to bring about such\na drastic change of heart.
Any guesses as to what it was?
That was what I was hoping to\nmake him tell us...but he offed\nhimself before I could.
It sounded like the priest who was\nmurdered had grown distrustful of\nhim, and they started arguing a lot.
Eventually, he started to suspect that his\nlife was in danger, and asked us for help...\nbut we were too late to save him.
Then, the bishop decided to murder that\npriest and pin the crime on the apostle\nwho came to aid his victim.
No doubt his aim was to weaken the\napostles' standing in the Church.
But I find it hard to believe the bishop\nwas the real root of all this. Someone\nelse was pulling the strings.
A shame that our only lead is dead.\nNow we've got no way of finding out.
As soon as I laid eyes on that bishop,\nI knew he wanted to do me harm.
Even so, that animosity felt almost...\nsurface-level. If only I'd had a proper\nconversation with him.
If only I wasn't such a coward,\nthis might have ended better...\nI'm sorry.
Nobody's blaming you for this, Ryszarda.
Yeah. If anything, your unique qualities\nmight've been what helped solve this.
Your unnaturally sharp instincts come\nfrom how timid you are.
I'd argue there's nothing inherently\nbad about you being that way.
On this matter, I must agree.
Before I sent you cascading off that cliff,\nyou understood what we wanted you to\ndo from our words and expressions.
You could do that because you are always\nobserving people. What you consider your\nweakness became your strength.
You're right that I could tell as soon\nas I saw you that you were just trying\nto get me away from the Templars.
But I think that was mostly because it\nwas you two. Since we're...well, friends.
I could surmise your intentions without\nyou putting them into words.
Now that's true trust in action!\nI'm a little jealous of you all.
I hope I can get to that point\nwith the rest of you, too!
Well, I don't know how dependable\nI'll be...but it would be my pleasure.

A quick caveat, though: no matter how
much you trust me, please don't go
flinging me off of any cliffs.
That's only okay with Ryszarda.
*sigh* Must you bring that up again?
This matter has been sufficiently\ndiscussed. Heed meâ€”I must apprise\nyou of your next mission.
I've always been more fainthearted than most,\nand have always hated that about myself.
But then Raphael told me to count on her\nand my friends, just like she depends on me.
That made realize that trust goes two ways.\nI don't just need my friendsâ€”they need me, too.
Simply knowing that is enough to quell my\nimpulse to turn tail and run from everything.\nProbably. Maybe. I think.
That concludes my explanation.\nFulfill your task in the Goddess's name.
By Her name, it shall be done!
I might be a coward, but I'm not aloneâ€”\nbecause I have the other apostles by my side!
